ng the Canard from its birth in 1915 to the eve of the Great Depression, the narrative reveals a heady mix of word play, word games, and cartoons. Over the years the journal--generally leftist, specifically antimilitarist and anti-imperialist--aimed its shots in all directions, using some stereotypes the twenty-first century might find unacceptable. But Douglas calls its humor an affirmation of life, and as such the most effective antidote to war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFrench wit and humorxHistory and criticism. 0aSatire, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vHumor. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xPress coveragezFrance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aarmistice.  abattles.  abodies.  acanard enchaine.  acannibalism.  acarnage.  acartoons.  acorpses.  acrossdressing.  adissent.  afrance.  afree press.  agender.  agreat depression.  agreat war.  ahistory.  ahumor.  aimperialism.  ainjured soldiers.  ajournalism.  aleftist politics.  aliterary criticism.  amilitarism.  amilitary.  anewspaper.  aperiodicals.  apolitical cartoons.  apolitical commentary.  apolitical speech.  aprotest.  asatire.  asocial commentary.  asoldier.  awar hero.  awar wounded.  awar.  aworld war one.  aww1.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022876440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092694340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926943/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY